    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the vet thing but i'm trying to read the labels myself to be prepared. i'm seeing some brands that are like 35% protein and 15% fat, while others are way higher in fat. is that high fat ratio bad for an older dog or is it fine as long as the protein is high?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While high protein is important, extremely high fat content can sometimes be an issue for older dogs, especially if they have kidney concerns or are prone to pancreatitis. A 35% protein and 15% fat combination is often a very well-balanced starting point for maintenance in a senior dog. The quality of the fats matters too; look for omega fatty acids like EPA and DHA. Always ensure the overall nutrition profile supports their joint health and digestion.",
      "source": "target",
